      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why Z Is the Best High-Value Tile in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>Z and Q share the throne at 10 points each, but Z is universally considered the better draw. Here's why: Q needs a U to unlock most of its words (QUEEN, QUILT, QUIZ), and if you don't have a U, you're limited to QI and a handful of others. Z has no such dependency. It works with any vowel (ZA, ZE, ZI, ZO, ZU) and has abundant short-word options.</p>
      <p>Z also benefits from appearing in many common English words that opponents overlook. ZONE, ZEAL, ZINC, ZAP — these aren't obscure tournament words; they're everyday vocabulary that happens to score 13-15 points each. Combined with premium squares, Z routinely produces 30-50 point turns.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Strategy for Playing Z-Words</h2>
      <p>Z is already powerful — these strategies make it devastating:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Triple-letter Z = 30 points from one tile:</strong> Always scan for triple-letter squares first. Z on a TLS is worth 30 points before you even count the rest of the word. This is the single highest-value tile placement in the game.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZA is your ultimate parallel play:</strong> ZA (11 pts) for a two-letter word is incredible. Place it parallel to an existing word to form multiple crosswords simultaneously — easy 25-40 point turns.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZAX for the X+Z jackpot:</strong> If you draw both Z and X, ZAX (19 pts base) puts both power tiles in one 3-letter word. On premium squares, this is a game-winning play.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Don't hold Z past mid-game:</strong> Z is worth 10 points — if you're stuck with it at game end, you lose those 10 points and your opponent gains them. A 20-point swing. Play it by turn 10-12 at the latest.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>ZONE and ZERO as reliable fallbacks:</strong> Can't find a premium square? ZONE (13 pts) and ZERO (13 pts) are common, easy-to-remember plays that always score respectably.</span></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Z vs Q — The Ultimate Comparison</h2>
      <p>Both worth 10 points, but Z wins the flexibility contest hands-down:</p>
      <ul class="not-prose space-y-2 my-4">
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Two-letter words:</strong> Z has ZA and ZO (11 pts each). Q only has QI (11 pts). Z has double the short-word options.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>U dependency:</strong> Z works independently. Q is crippled without U (only QI, QOPH, QADI, QANAT work without U).</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>Word variety:</strong> Z has 100+ common words. Q's best plays (QUIZ, QUEEN, QUILT) all require U to be available.</span></li>
        <li class="flex items-start gap-2 text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-blue-500 mt-0.5 shrink-0">▶</span><span><strong>End-game risk:</strong> Being stuck with Q costs 10 pts and Q is harder to play late. Z can almost always be dumped for 11+ points via ZA or ZO.</span></li>
      </ul>

